    <div class="tldr-box" role="region" aria-label="Summary">
      <span class="tldr-label">The short answer</span>
      <p><strong>Canada leads the world</strong> with 65% of adults holding a tertiary degree, followed by Ireland (58%), Japan (57%), and South Korea (56%). But raw attainment rankings tell only part of the story. South Korea produces a disproportionate share of engineers. Finland&rsquo;s teacher quality is unmatched. Israel leads the world in researchers per capita. Germany&rsquo;s dual-education system produces tradespeople so effectively that its youth unemployment is among the lowest on Earth. India produces more STEM graduates by raw volume than any country.</p>
      <p>The deepest insight in this data is the <strong>access-vs-performance paradox</strong>: Iceland has among the world&rsquo;s highest mean years of schooling (13.9) but PISA scores below the OECD average, while Singapore achieves the world&rsquo;s best PISA results with only 12 years of average schooling. More school does not mean better outcomes. System design matters more than seat time.</p>
    </div>


    <!-- ═══════════ PART 1 ═══════════ -->
    <div class="part-header" id="part1">
      <span class="part-label">Part 1</span>
      <h2 class="part-title">The Full Ranking: Tertiary Attainment by Country</h2>
    </div>

    <p>The most comprehensive comparable dataset comes from the OECD&rsquo;s <em>Education at a Glance 2025</em> (released September 2025, reference year mostly 2024). Table A1.1 ranks adults aged 25&ndash;64 by the percentage whose highest qualification is tertiary (ISCED 5&ndash;8: short-cycle tertiary, bachelor&rsquo;s, master&rsquo;s, or doctoral). The OECD average is 42%. The EU25 average is 39%. The G20 average is 34%.</p>

