    <span class="section-label">The generational shift: 25&ndash;34 year-olds</span>

    <p>The ranking changes dramatically when you isolate younger adults. The OECD average for 25&ndash;34 year-olds jumps to 48% (up from 27% in 2000). South Korea stands out most strikingly: roughly 70&ndash;71% of its 25&ndash;34 year-olds hold tertiary qualifications, compared to only ~28% of its 55&ndash;64 year-olds &mdash; a 42-point generational gap reflecting one of the fastest education expansions in human history. Canada also exceeds 68% in the younger bracket.</p>

    <div class="part-takeaway">
      <strong>Part 1 takeaway</strong>
      Canada leads overall (65%), but South Korea leads the younger generation (~71% for 25&ndash;34). Rankings depend heavily on which age bracket and which definition of &ldquo;tertiary&rdquo; you use. The OECD covers ~47 countries reliably; non-OECD global data is patchier.
    </div>


    <!-- ═══════════ PART 2 ═══════════ -->
    <div class="part-header" id="part2">
      <span class="part-label">Part 2</span>
      <h2 class="part-title">What Each Top Country Specifically Excels In</h2>
    </div>

    <p>Raw attainment percentages tell you who has the most degrees. They don&rsquo;t tell you what those countries are actually <em>good at</em>. Here&rsquo;s what the specialized data shows for each top-third country.</p>

    <div class="table-scroll">
      <table class="data-table" aria-label="Top-third countries and their specific areas of excellence">
        <thead><tr><th>Country</th><th>Specific Excellence</th><th>Key Data Point</th><th>Source</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>South Korea</strong></td><td>Engineers &amp; STEM graduates</td><td>~25&ndash;30% of tertiary grads in engineering/manufacturing (vs. OECD ~15&ndash;20%); ~9,435 researchers per million (among global tops)</td><td>OECD Table A1.3; UNESCO UIS R&amp;D</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Finland</strong></td><td>Teacher quality</td><td>All teachers require master&rsquo;s degree; top ~10% of applicants accepted; 49% salary-satisfied (vs. OECD 39%)</td><td>OECD TALIS 2024; national policy</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Israel</strong></td><td>Scientists &amp; researchers per capita</td><td>R&amp;D spend ~5.5&ndash;6% of GDP (world #1); researchers per million among highest globally</td><td>UNESCO UIS; World Bank R&amp;D data</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Germany</strong></td><td>Dual vocational/trades system</td><td>~50% of school-leavers enter dual VET; ~1.2M apprentices; youth unemployment ~5&ndash;6% (OECD lowest)</td><td>OECD; national stats 2023/24</td></tr>
